/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:7:### F-001: Caller-controlled allowance targets can leave persistent approvals that later drain stranded tokens
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:13:**Impact:** Any same-token balance that later becomes stranded in the zapper can be stolen by the approved spender via `transferFrom` before governance sweeps it. Realistic sources of stranded balance include mistaken transfers, airdrops, overpaid native ETH handling, and other token-movement failures.
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:21:- The allowance persists after the transaction and the attacker later uses `transferFrom(zapper, attacker, amount)` to drain any future stranded balance of that token
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:73:**Impact:** If the batcher ever under-delivers, rounds down, or partially fulfills while the zapper already holds residual want tokens, the caller can consume that residue as if it were part of their own withdrawal. This can misattribute previously stranded funds to the next zap-out caller.
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:95:**Impact:** Users who overpay ETH lose the surplus immediately, and governance can later capture that stranded ETH through `sweep(nativeETH)`.
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/brahtopg_p5_25_124/final_report.md:103:- The surplus remains stranded until governance sweeps it
