/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/moloch_test/rounds/round_1/merge_prompt.md:119:[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Futarchy reward pools are only accounted for, not escrowed, so winners can be left with unpayable receipts","locations":["Moloch.sol:336","Moloch.sol:565","Moloch.sol:569","Moloch.sol:521","Moloch.sol:616","Moloch.sol:988"],"claim":"The futarchy system records reward balances in `F.pool` and computes `payoutPerUnit` from that accounting value, but it never escrows or reserves the underlying ETH/ERC20/share/loot assets. The same treasury assets remain spendable by normal DAO actions, and YES-path execution even runs arbitrary proposal code before futarchy resolution.","impact":"Winning receipt holders can end up with claims that revert or are only partially honorable because the DAO has already spent the assets that `F.pool` assumes still exist. This breaks the payout guarantee of the market and lets a passing proposal or later treasury action drain rewards owed to winners.","paths":["Open or fund a futarchy market using ETH/ERC20/local shares/local loot so `F.pool` increases.","Before winners cash out, spend the same treasury assets via a proposal, sale, allowance withdrawal, or other treasury path.","On YES outcomes, `executeByVotes()` performs `_execute(...)` before `_resolveFutarchyYes()`, so the executed proposal itself can consume the would-be reward pool first.","`cashOutFutarchy()` later pays from the live treasury via `_payout(...)`, which reverts or underfunds if the assets are gone."]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"BondingCurveSale exact-in buys can undercharge when the solver overshoots","locations":["peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:176","peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:183","peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:209","peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:211","peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:214","peripheral/BondingCurveSale.sol:223"],"claim":"`buyExactIn()` derives `amount` analytically for LINEAR/XYK curves, then if `_cost(...)` is greater than `msg.value` it clamps `cost` down to `msg.value` instead of reducing `amount`. The buyer still receives the full overshot token amount.","impact":"Exact-in buyers can obtain more sale inventory than they actually paid for. Even if each trade only extracts rounding-sized value, the discrepancy is repeatable and drains DAO sale inventory at a discount.","paths":["Configure a LINEAR or XYK bonding-curve sale.","Call `buyExactIn()` with a value that makes the analytical `amount` slightly too large once `_cost(...)` is recomputed with rounded-up pricing.","The function sets `cost = msg.value`, spends allowance for the oversized `amount`, and transfers all of those shares/loot to the buyer."]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Proposal-threshold checks use current votes while snapshots use the previous block, enabling same-block threshold bypass","locations":["Moloch.sol:283","Moloch.sol:285","Moloch.sol:290","Moloch.sol:347"],"claim":"`openProposal()` enforces `proposalThreshold` with `getVotes(msg.sender)` from the current block, but fixes the proposal snapshot at `block.number - 1`. A proposer can temporarily acquire delegated votes in the current block, open the proposal, and then be evaluated against a snapshot where those votes never existed.","impact":"The proposal threshold no longer reliably gates proposal creation. Attackers can use transient voting power to open spam proposals they could not have opened at the actual voting snapshot, which also compounds with any features triggered on proposal open.","paths":["Temporarily obtain enough delegated votes in the current block.","Call `openProposal()` or `castVote()` (which auto-opens) before the borrowed votes disappear.","The threshold passes on current votes, while the proposal snapshot is fixed to the previous block where the proposer did not hold those votes."]}]
