/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/sandbox_dualmodel_1round_p4/rounds/round_1/merge_stderr.log:472:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Public `_burn` lets anyone destroy arbitrary LAND and corrupt balances","locations":["0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:355","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:356","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:357","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:358"],"claim":"`_burn` is declared `public` and only checks the caller-supplied `from` and `owner` arguments for equality. It never verifies `msg.sender`, token existence, or that `owner` matches the real owner resolved by `_ownerOf`/`_ownerAndOperatorEnabledOf`. Any external account can therefore call `_burn(victim, victim, id)` and overwrite arbitrary `_owners[id]` slots with the burn sentinel while decrementing any chosen address balance.","impact":"An attacker can permissionlessly burn live LAND parcels belonging to other users, permanently tombstone unminted 1x1 ids or internal quad-layer storage slots so they can never be minted/regrouped, and underflow arbitrary `_numNFTPerAddress` balances by burning nonexistent ids. This can destroy user assets, brick future supply, and corrupt accounting.","paths":["Call `_burn(alice, alice, childId)` for a live LAND tile owned by Alice; the function sets `_owners[childId] = 2**160` and decrements Alice's balance without any authorization check.","Call `_burn(target, target, nonexistentId)`; because there is no existence check, `_numNFTPerAddress[target]--` executes and can underflow if the target balance is too small.","Call `_burn(victim, victim, LAYER_3x3/6x6/12x12/24x24 + baseId)` to tombstone internal quad slots, causing future mint/regroup logic that expects zeroed storage to fail permanently."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Burning one child LAND permanently breaks transfers of enclosing quads","locations":["0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:357","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:281","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:284","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:426","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:432"],"claim":"Burning sets `_owners[id] = 2**160` as a sentinel. `LandBaseToken._ownerOf()` casts that value down to `address(0)`, so burned children look nonexistent to ownership queries. But regrouping uses `_checkAndClear()`, which treats any nonzero raw storage value as an owned slot and requires `address(owner) == from`. For the burn sentinel this becomes `address(2**160) == from`, i.e. `address(0) == from`, which can never hold for a valid owner.","impact":"After any authorized burn of a 1x1 parcel inside a 3x3/6x6/12x12/24x24 region, later `transferQuad` or `batchTransferQuad` calls that need to regroup that enclosing area revert forever. A single burned tile can therefore permanently lock high-value quads from being transferred as quads and force owners into fragmented management of the remaining parcels.","paths":["A user owns a 24x24 quad and burns one child tile via `burn(id)` or `burnFrom(from, id)`.","Later the owner calls `transferQuad(from, to, 24, x, y, data)` or any enclosing `12`, `6`, or `3` regroup.","During `_regroup*`, `_checkAndClear()` encounters the burned child, sees a nonzero storage slot, and reverts with `not owner`, blocking the quad transfer permanently."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Quad mints and quad transfers can silently lock LAND in contracts that lack the custom batch receiver interface","locations":["0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:153","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:194","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/ERC721BaseToken.sol:265","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:156","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:202","0x50f5474724e0ee42d9a4e711ccfb275809fd6d4a/src/Land/erc721/LandBaseToken.sol:249"],"claim":"`mintQuad`, `transferQuad`, and `batchTransferQuad` only perform receiver validation when the destination is a contract that both answers ERC165 within the hard-coded 10,000 gas budget and claims support for the custom `ERC721MandatoryTokenReceiver` interface. Contracts that implement only standard `onERC721Received`, omit ERC165, or have an expensive `supportsInterface` are treated as if no callback is required, so the quad transfer/mint succeeds without any acceptance check.","impact":"Users can mint or transfer up to 576 LAND tiles into contracts that cannot handle or release them, permanently locking the assets. Because the quad APIs have no strict safe variant that enforces receiver acceptance, callers cannot reliably force on-chain validation before moving an entire quad.","paths":["A minter calls `mintQuad` to a contract that is not an EOA but does not expose ERC165 support for `ERC721MandatoryTokenReceiver`; the mint succeeds without any callback.","A user calls `transferQuad` or `batchTransferQuad` to a marketplace/vault that only implements standard ERC721 receiving logic; the transfer bypasses the receiver check and strands the LAND.","A receiver contract does implement ERC165, but its `supportsInterface` path exceeds the 10,000 gas budget; `_checkInterfaceWith10000Gas` returns false and the protocol skips acceptance checks anyway."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Super Operators can arbitrarily transfer any user's tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an explicit admin-controlled trust role by design: transfer authorization intentionally includes `_superOperators[msg.sender]`. It is a centralization/property-of-privileged-role concern, not a permissionless vulnerability."},{"title":"approveFor allows setting approval on tokens user doesn't own","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`approveFor` requires `msg.sender` to be the `sender`, a trusted meta-tx processor, a super operator, or an already-approved operator-for-all, and separately requires `owner == sender`. The cited unauthorized path is not supported by the code."},{"title":"setApprovalForAllFor allows super operators to self-approve","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Super operators already have global transfer power, so self-approval adds no new capability or exploitable permissionless path. This is redundant with the intended privileged role."},{"title":"Missing zero-address validation when changing admin","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Setting admin to `address(0)` is an admin-only misconfiguration risk, not an externally exploitable protocol vulnerability. It does not create realistic permissionless fund loss by itself."},{"title":"Land contract does not implement ERC-165 supportsInterface correctly","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`supportsInterface` correctly returns true for the three advertised interface IDs and false otherwise. The claim about 'multiple interface IDs' is not meaningful for ERC-165, which checks one `bytes4` at a time."},{"title":"batchTransferFrom does not verify token existence before transfer","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_batchTransferFrom` loads `(owner, operatorEnabled)` via `_ownerAndOperatorEnabledOf(id)` and requires `owner == from`, while `from` must be nonzero. Unminted tokens resolve to `owner == address(0)` and cannot pass the check."},{"title":"No two-step process for admin transfer creates permanent lockup risk","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance best-practice issue only. It depends on operator mistake and does not describe a concrete exploitable protocol flaw."},{"title":"mintQuad can overflow when calculating token count","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`size` is strictly constrained to `1`, `3`, `6`, `12`, or `24`, so `size * size` is at most `576`. The proposed overflow cannot occur in the reachable code path."},{"title":"setMinter lacks zero-address validation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Allowing `address(0)` in the minter mapping is benign configuration noise; it does not grant power or create an exploitable state transition."},{"title":"MetaTransactionReceiver allows setting any address as meta transaction processor","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an admin-trusted configuration choice. Pointing the processor to an EOA may disable or centralize meta-tx handling, but it is not a standalone permissionless vulnerability."}]}
